In June, both Governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalists argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic population, most in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign questioned whether the participation would reach the minimum 50 % required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The paper of the referendum raised the question: "Is it in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
The name change players, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claim that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerge from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies such as the EU and NATO.
"Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the young of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the European Union, because this means a safer life for all," said 79-year-old Oliver Georgievska in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said that they will respect the outcome of the vote in order to be decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that no irregularities had been reported at one in the afternoon.
However, participation was only 16%, compared with 34% of the last elections to Parliament held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters deposited their vote.
"I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
Zoran Zaev, the prime minister of Macedonia, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko deposited their vote at the Macedonia referendum on a change of name for the country that would open the way to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on 30 September 2018.
In front of Parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and removed chairs from the campaign shops that were to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of entering NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with a very high head, not by the back door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of European integration."
Prime Minister Zaev said that NATO membership would provide the investment that Macedonia needs so much, with unemployment rates above 20%.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80% of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after depositing his vote.
He said that a positive result would be a "confirmation of our future".
