A 2014 survey carried out by the UK Employment and Competence Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons for the difficulties faced by entrepreneurs were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Linguistic skills are therefore increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race that someone chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last all your life.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will allow that person to advance automatically to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language as well as to keep a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If you know a number of languages, especially those from developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each college will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the most important languages for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Anyone who is interested in a child, in independent colleges, will always be able to choose from a number of languages provided by teaching staff specialized in this matter.
Independent education centres in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the necessary skills to succeed, whatever the future holds them.
At the moment, it is unmistakable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competence for international communication".
Independent colleges will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to the young people in Scotland.
