Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course this year at Harvard University, all university students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing machist culture to study all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that university students number one in the world often have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of his class in the U.S.
His motivation to launch the course arose after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached and asked me why she had just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever talked to him about the importance of the dream, which surprised me," The Telegraph commented.
The course, conducted for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the health services of the university, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that the students only slept during the week.
The course of one hour includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of the lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression and cancer.
Then, an icon of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students at the moment.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know the effects on tobacco smoking health," added Professor Czeisler.
He said that the culture of pride for "passing the night on a sail" still exists and added that modern technology and increasing pressure to which students are subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough time and a good quality dream should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gain weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year in Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study programme before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler's recommendation is that students think about putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emits the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the circadian rhythms, so they would end up having problems to stay asleep.
