Update of the red tide: Reduces concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (Commission of Fisheries and Fauna and Flora de Florida) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends about 130 miles along the coast from the Pinellas County to the north to the Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less places if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Easter County.
During the last week, average concentrations have been reported in the County of Pinellas and on its coast, low and high concentrations in the County of Hillsborough, high background concentrations in the County of Manatee, high background concentrations in the County of Sarasota and its coast, medium background concentrations in the County of Charlotte, high background concentrations in the County of Lee and on its coast, and low concentrations in the County of Collier.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation problems in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in the northwest of Florida during the last week.
